# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Four Pillars of JavaScript Extension

### Pillar 1: ES6+ Modern Language Features

ES6 (released **June 2015**) and subsequent yearly releases introduced syntax sugar and structural upgrades. KTU examiners most frequently test the following:

#### a) `let`, `const`, and Block Scoping

| Keyword | Scope | Reassignable? | Hoisted? |
|:---|:---|:---|:---|
| `var` | Function-scoped | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes (undefined) |
| `let` | Block-scoped (`{}`) | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (TDZ) |
| `const` | Block-scoped (`{}`) | ❌ No | ❌ No (TDZ) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **TDZ (Temporal Dead Zone):** The period between entering a block and the declaration of a `let`/`const` variable, where accessing the variable throws a `ReferenceError`. This is a **favourite KTU 2-mark question**.

#### b) Arrow Functions

Compact syntax for anonymous functions. **Critical property:** Arrow functions do **NOT** bind their own `this` — they inherit it lexically from the enclosing scope.

$$ \text{Arrow Function Syntax: } (args) \Rightarrow \text{ expression} $$

Equivalent ES5:

```javascript
// ES5
var add = function(a, b) { return a + b; };

// ES6+
const add = (a, b) => a + b;
```

#### c) Template Literals

```javascript
const name = "KTU";
const greeting = `Hello, ${name}! Welcome to ${2024 + 1}.`;
// Output: "Hello, KTU! Welcome to 2025."
```

> [!NOTE]
> Use **backticks** (`` ` ``), not single quotes. Supports **multi-line strings** and **expression interpolation** `${...}`.

#### d) Destructuring

Extract values from arrays/objects into distinct variables.

```javascript
// Object destructuring
const student = { name: "Anu", cgpa: 9.2, branch: "CSE" };
const { name, cgpa } = student;

// Array destructuring
const [first, second] = ["React", "Angular"];
```

#### e) Spread (`...`) and Rest (`...`) Operators

| Operator | Context | Purpose |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **Spread** | Function call / array literal | Expands an iterable into individual elements |
| **Rest** | Function parameter / destructuring | Collects multiple elements into a single array |

```javascript
// Spread: combine arrays
const merged = [...arr1, ...arr2];

// Rest: collect arguments
const sum = (...nums) => nums.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
```

#### f) Classes (Syntactic Sugar over Prototypes)

ES6 classes provide **cleaner OOP syntax** over the prototype-based inheritance of ES5.

```javascript
class Vehicle {
  constructor(type, speed) {
    this.type = type;
    this.speed = speed;
  }
  describe() { return `${this.type} runs at ${this.speed} km/h`; }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
  constructor(speed) { super("Car", speed); }
}
```

#### g) Modules (`import` / `export`)

```javascript
// math.js
export const pi = 3.14;
export default function add(a, b) { return a + b; }

// app.js
import add, { pi } from './math.js';
```

---

### Pillar 2: Asynchronous JavaScript — Promises & async/await

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Asynchronous execution** means JavaScript doesn't block the main thread while waiting for long-running operations (network requests, file reads, timers). The **Event Loop** orchestrates this.

#### The Evolution of Async Code

| Era | Mechanism | Drawback |
|:---|:---|:---|
| ES5 | **Callback functions** | "Callback Hell" — nested, unreadable code |
| ES6 (2015) | **Promises** | Still requires `.then().catch()` chaining |
| ES8 (2017) | **async / await** | Syntactic sugar over Promises — **cleanest** |

#### What is a Promise?

> [!NOTE]
> A **Promise** is an object representing the **eventual completion (or failure)** of an asynchronous operation. It is a **placeholder for a future value**.

**Promise States (Finite State Machine):**

$$ S_{\text{promise}} = \{\text{pending}, \text{fulfilled}, \text{rejected}\} $$

- `pending` → Initial state, neither resolved nor rejected.
- `fulfilled` → Operation completed successfully; has a `value`.
- `rejected` → Operation failed; has a `reason` (error).
- Once **settled** (fulfilled or rejected), state **CANNOT change** — this property is called **immutability of promises**.

#### The async/await Syntax

```javascript
async function fetchUserData(userId) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`);
    const data = await response.json();
    return data;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Fetch failed:", error);
  }
}
```

**Rule:** `await` can **only** be used inside a function declared with `async`. The `async` function **always returns a Promise**.

---

### Pillar 3: AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **AJAX** is **NOT a technology** — it is a **technique/pattern** for sending and receiving data **asynchronously** from a server, **without a full page reload**. The original implementation used the **`XMLHttpRequest` (XHR)** object; modern AJAX uses the **Fetch API**.

**Classic XHR Workflow:**

$$ \text{Client} \xrightarrow{\text{XHR.send()}} \text{Server} \xrightarrow{\text{HTTP Response}} \text{Client (DOM update)} $$

```javascript
const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open("GET", "https://api.ktu.edu/results", true); // true = async
xhr.onload = function() {
  if (xhr.status === 200) {
    const data = JSON.parse(xhr.responseText);
    console.log(data);
  }
};
xhr.onerror = () => console.error("Network Error");
xhr.send();
```

**AJAX Properties (Frequent 3-Mark Questions):**

| Property/Method | Purpose |
|:---|:---|
| `xhr.open(method, url, async)` | Initializes the request |
| `xhr.send(body)` | Sends the request |
| `xhr.onreadystatechange` | Fires on every state change (0→4) |
| `xhr.readyState` | 0=UNSENT, 1=OPENED, 2=HEADERS_RECEIVED, 3=LOADING, 4=DONE |
| `xhr.status` | HTTP status code (200, 404, 500, etc.) |
| `xhr.responseText` | Response as a string |

---

### Pillar 4: JSON (JavaScript Object Notation)

> [!NOTE]
> **JSON** is a **lightweight, text-based, language-independent data interchange format** derived from JavaScript object literal syntax. It is the **de-facto standard** for AJAX/REST API communication.

**JSON Syntax Rules:**

1. Data is in **key/value pairs**: `"key": "value"`
2. Data is separated by **commas**
3. Objects are enclosed in **curly braces** `{}`
4. Arrays are enclosed in **square brackets** `[]`
5. **Strings MUST be in double quotes** (not single quotes)
6. **No comments allowed**
7. **No trailing commas**

**JSON vs XML — KTU Comparison Table (High-Yield!):**

| Feature | JSON | XML |
|:---|:---|:---|
| Full form | JavaScript Object Notation | Extensible Markup Language |
| Syntax | Lightweight, key-value | Tag-based, verbose |
| Data types | String, number, boolean, null, array, object | All data as text (string) |
| Parsing | Native `JSON.parse()` in JS | Requires DOMParser or library |
| Size | **Smaller** (~30-40% less) | Larger |
| Comments | ❌ Not allowed | ✅ Allowed `<!-- -->` |
| Schema | Optional (JSON Schema) | XSD, DTD |
| Readability | High (for simple data) | High (for complex docs) |
| Speed | **Faster parsing** | Slower |
| Use case | REST APIs, config files | SOAP, document markup |

**JSON Methods in JavaScript:**

$$ \text{Object} \xleftrightarrow{\text{JSON.stringify(obj)}}{\text{JSON.parse(str)}} \text{JSON String} $$

```javascript
const obj = { name: "Anu", age: 21, skills: ["JS", "React"] };

// Object → JSON string
const str = JSON.stringify(obj); 
// '{"name":"Anu","age":21,"skills":["JS","React"]}'

// JSON string → Object
const parsed = JSON.parse(str);  // { name: "Anu", age: 21, ... }
```

---

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet (Master Reference)

| # | Concept | Syntax / Formula | Key Point |
|:---:|:---|:---|:---|
| 1 | Block scoping | `let x = 10;` inside `{}` | TDZ exists before declaration |
| 2 | Arrow function | `(a, b) => a + b` | No own `this` binding |
| 3 | Template literal | `` `Hello ${name}` `` | Backticks + `${}` |
| 4 | Destructuring | `const {a, b} = obj;` | Extracts properties |
| 5 | Spread | `[...arr1, ...arr2]` | Expands iterable |
| 6 | Rest | `(...args) => {}` | Collects into array |
| 7 | Class | `class A extends B {}` | Sugar over prototypes |
| 8 | Module export | `export default x;` | One default per file |
| 9 | Module import | `import x from './f.js';` | Path must have extension |
| 10 | Promise states | `{pending, fulfilled, rejected}` | Immutable after settle |
| 11 | async function | `async function f() { ... }` | Returns Promise |
| 12 | await | `const r = await fetch(url);` | Only inside `async` |
| 13 | XHR readyState | $\{0,1,2,3,4\}$ | $4$ = DONE |
| 14 | JSON stringify | `JSON.stringify(obj)` | Object → String |
| 15 | JSON parse | `JSON.parse(str)` | String → Object |
| 16 | Fetch default | `fetch(url)` | GET request, returns Promise |

