# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations, Examples & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Exhaustive Example: `var` vs `let` in Loops (Classic KTU Question)

This is a **very frequently asked KTU question** (Dec 2021, May 2022) — *"Explain the output of the following code with `var` and `let`."*

### Problem Statement

Predict the output of the following two code snippets:

**Code A (using `var`):**
```javascript
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100);
}
```

**Code B (using `let`):**
```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100);
}
```

### Step-by-Step Analysis

#### Analysis of Code A (using `var`)

**Step 1 — Declaration phase:**
`var i` is **function-scoped** (or globally scoped if outside any function). Even though it appears inside the `for` block, it is **hoisted** to the enclosing function/global scope.

**Step 2 — Loop iteration:**
At the end of each loop iteration, the value of `i` is updated in the **same shared variable**.

**Step 3 — Callback queuing:**
The `setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100)` registers three callbacks. They will all execute **after 100 ms**, **after the loop has fully finished**.

**Step 4 — Final value of `i`:**
After the loop completes, `i = 3` (because the loop terminates when `i < 3` fails).

**Step 5 — Execution of callbacks:**
When the callbacks run, they all reference the **same variable `i`**, which now holds the value **3**.

**Output of Code A:**
```
3
3
3
```

#### Analysis of Code B (using `let`)

**Step 1 — Block scoping:**
`let i` is **block-scoped**. A **new binding of `i`** is created for **each iteration** of the loop.

**Step 2 — Per-iteration binding:**
Iteration 1 → `i = 0` (binding #1)
Iteration 2 → `i = 1` (binding #2)
Iteration 3 → `i = 2` (binding #3)

**Step 3 — Closure capture:**
Each arrow function `() => console.log(i)` captures **its own binding** of `i` from the enclosing block.

**Step 4 — Output:**
When the timeouts fire, each callback reads its own captured value.

**Output of Code B:**
```
0
1
2
```

### Analytical Matrix

| Aspect | `var` (Code A) | `let` (Code B) |
|:---|:---|:---|
| Scope type | Function | Block |
| Number of bindings | **1** (shared) | **3** (one per iteration) |
| Final value of `i` | 3 | 2 |
| Output sequence | `3, 3, 3` | `0, 1, 2` |
| Why? | Single variable, mutated | New binding per loop iteration |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **This is the most-asked KTU question on `var` vs `let`.** Memorize the reasoning — *block scoping creates a new binding per iteration*.

---

## 3.2 Exhaustive Example: Promise Chaining → async/await Conversion

**KTU 2024 expects you to be able to convert between callback-style, Promise-style, and async/await-style code.**

### Original Callback-Hell Style (ES5)

```javascript
function getUser(id, callback) {
  setTimeout(() => callback(null, { id, name: "Anu" }), 100);
}

function getPosts(user, callback) {
  setTimeout(() => callback(null, ["Post1", "Post2"]), 100);
}

getUser(1, (err, user) => {
  if (err) return console.error(err);
  getPosts(user, (err, posts) => {
    if (err) return console.error(err);
    console.log(user.name, posts);
    // "Pyramid of Doom" — nested 3+ levels deep
  });
});
```

### Step 1 — Refactor to Promise Style (ES6)

Each function returns a `Promise`:

```javascript
function getUser(id) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    setTimeout(() => resolve({ id, name: "Anu" }), 100);
  });
}

function getPosts(user) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    setTimeout(() => resolve(["Post1", "Post2"]), 100);
  });
}

getUser(1)
  .then(user => getPosts(user))
  .then(posts => console.log("Anu", posts))
  .catch(err => console.error(err));
```

**Step-by-step conversion logic:**
- `callback(null, value)` becomes `resolve(value)`.
- `callback(err, null)` becomes `reject(err)` (caught by `.catch`).
- Nested callbacks become **chained `.then()` calls**.
- Errors propagate automatically through `.catch()`.

### Step 2 — Refactor to async/await Style (ES8+)

```javascript
async function showUserPosts() {
  try {
    const user = await getUser(1);     // waits for promise
    const posts = await getPosts(user); // waits for promise
    console.log(user.name, posts);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err);
  }
}
showUserPosts();
```

**Conversion Logic Table:**

| Promise Style | async/await Style |
|:---|:---|
| `function f() { return new Promise(...); }` | `async function f() { ... }` |
| `.then(value => ...)` | `const value = await promise;` |
| `.catch(err => ...)` | `try { ... } catch(err) { ... }` |
| Nested `.then()` | Sequential `await` statements |

> [!NOTE]
> **Under the hood**, `async/await` is **syntactic sugar** over Promises. The `await` keyword **pauses execution** of the `async` function until the awaited Promise settles, while **NOT blocking the main thread** of JavaScript (other tasks continue).

---

## 3.3 Exhaustive Example: AJAX XHR State Transition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU frequently asks:** *"Explain the `readyState` lifecycle of an XMLHttpRequest object."* Here's the exhaustive step-by-step.

### The 5-State Machine of XHR

| `readyState` | Name | Description | `status` available? |
|:---:|:---|:---|:---|
| **0** | `UNSENT` | Client created, `open()` not called | ❌ |
| **1** | `OPENED` | `open()` called, `send()` not called | ❌ |
| **2** | `HEADERS_RECEIVED` | `send()` called, headers + status received | ✅ |
| **3** | `LOADING` | Downloading; `responseText` partial | ❌ (partial) |
| **4** | `DONE` | Operation complete (success or error) | ✅ |

### Step-by-Step Code Walkthrough

```javascript
const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
// State: 0 (UNSENT)

xhr.open("GET", "https://api.example.com/data", true);
// State: 1 (OPENED). Request is configured but not sent.

xhr.onreadystatechange = function() {
  console.log(`State: ${xhr.readyState}, Status: ${xhr.status}`);
  if (xhr.readyState === 4 && xhr.status === 200) {
    const data = JSON.parse(xhr.responseText);
    console.log(data);
  }
};

xhr.send();
// State progression: 1 → 2 → 3 → 4
// Each transition fires onreadystatechange once.
```

**Console output (approx):**
```
State: 1, Status: 0
State: 2, Status: 200
State: 3, Status: 200
State: 4, Status: 200
{"name":"KTU","year":2024}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Better practice:** Use the **`xhr.onload`** event (fires only at state 4) instead of `onreadystatechange` to avoid manually checking `readyState === 4`.

---

## 3.4 Exhaustive Example: Building a JSON-Driven Student Directory

A **full KTU-style programming question** often asks: *"Fetch data from a JSON API and render it on a webpage."*

### Step 1 — Sample JSON File (`students.json`)

```json
{
  "department": "CSE",
  "students": [
    { "id": 1, "name": "Anu",   "cgpa": 9.2 },
    { "id": 2, "name": "Rahul", "cgpa": 8.7 },
    { "id": 3, "name": "Meera", "cgpa": 9.5 }
  ]
}
```

### Step 2 — Fetch Using Fetch API + async/await

```javascript
async function loadStudents() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch("students.json");

    if (!response.ok) {            // Check HTTP status
      throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);
    }

    const data = await response.json();
    console.log(`Dept: ${data.department}`);

    const list = data.students
      .filter(s => s.cgpa >= 9.0)
      .map(s => `${s.name} (${s.cgpa})`)
      .join("\n");

    console.log("Top Students:\n" + list);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("Failed:", err.message);
  }
}

loadStudents();
```

### Step 3 — Expected Output

```
Dept: CSE
Top Students:
Anu (9.2)
Meera (9.5)
```

**Step-by-step reasoning:**
1. `fetch()` returns a `Promise<Response>`.
2. `await` pauses until response arrives.
3. `response.ok` is `true` for HTTP status **200–299**.
4. `response.json()` parses the body and returns a `Promise<Object>`.
5. `.filter()` keeps CGPA $\geq 9.0$.
6. `.map()` formats each student as `"Name (CGPA)"`.
7. `.join("\n")` concatenates with newlines.
8. `try/catch` handles network or parse errors.

