```

## 4.5 JSON vs XML — Comparative Block Diagram

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    subgraph JSON_Side[JSON Side]
        J1[Lightweight key value]
        J2[Native to JavaScript]
        J3[Arrays supported]
        J4[No comments]
        J5[Faster parsing]
        J6[REST APIs default]
    end

    subgraph XML_Side[XML Side]
        X1[Verbose tag based]
        X2[Language independent]
        X3[No native arrays]
        X4[Comments allowed]
        X5[Slower parsing]
        X6[SOAP legacy]
    end

    J1 --- X1
    J2 --- X2
    J3 --- X3
    J4 --- X4
    J5 --- X5
    J6 --- X6
```

## 4.6 Event Loop & Async Execution Model

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    subgraph CallStack[Call Stack Synchronous]
        CS1[Function 1]
        CS2[Function 2]
        CS3[Function 3]
    end

    subgraph WebAPIs[Browser Web APIs]
        WA1[setTimeout]
        WA2[fetch XHR]
        WA3[DOM Events]
    end

    subgraph CallbackQueue[Task Queue Callback Queue]
        CQ1[Callback 1]
        CQ2[Callback 2]
    end

    subgraph MicroTaskQueue[Microtask Queue Priority]
        MQ1[Promise then]
        MQ2[await continuations]
    end

    CallStack -->|Empty Event Loop| MicroTaskQueue
    MicroTaskQueue -->|Drain all first| CallbackQueue
    CallbackQueue -->|then push to stack| CallStack

    WebAPIs -->|Timer fires setTimeout| CallbackQueue
    WebAPIs -->|Promise resolves| MicroTaskQueue
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The Event Loop** continuously checks: *(1)* Is the Call Stack empty? *(2)* If yes, drain **all** microtasks (Promise callbacks) first, then process **one** macrotask (setTimeout, XHR) from the task queue. This is **why Promises resolve faster** than `setTimeout(..., 0)`.

