# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question A1 — `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Q: Explain the differences between `var`, `let`, and `const` in JavaScript with examples.**

**Model Answer:**

| Feature | `var` | `let` | `const` |
|:---|:---|:---|:---|
| **Scope** | Function-scoped | Block-scoped (`{}`) | Block-scoped (`{}`) |
| **Re-declaration** | Allowed in same scope | ❌ Not allowed | ❌ Not allowed |
| **Re-assignment** | ✅ Allowed | ✅ Allowed | ❌ Not allowed (binding is immutable) |
| **Hoisting** | Hoisted, initialized as `undefined` | Hoisted but in **TDZ** | Hoisted but in **TDZ** |
| **Global object property** | Creates `window.x` | Does not create `window.x` | Does not create `window.x` |

```javascript
function demo() {
  if (true) {
    var a = 10;   // function-scoped
    let b = 20;   // block-scoped
    const c = 30; // block-scoped
  }
  console.log(a); // 10
  console.log(b); // ReferenceError: b is not defined
  console.log(c); // ReferenceError
}
```

`const` makes the **binding** immutable, NOT the value. If the value is an object, its properties can still be mutated.

