## 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Internal Choice)

### Question A — `[KTU University Exam - May 2023]` — **14 Marks**

#### (a) — 7 Marks

**Explain the concept of Promises in JavaScript. Discuss the three states of a Promise with a suitable example.**

**Model Answer:**

A **Promise** in JavaScript is an object that represents the **eventual completion or failure** of an asynchronous operation. It acts as a **placeholder for a value that is not yet available** but will be resolved in the future. Promises were introduced in **ES6 (2015)** to solve the problem of "Callback Hell" in asynchronous programming.

**Syntax:**
```javascript
const myPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  // async operation
  if (success) resolve(value);
  else reject(error);
});
```

**The Three States of a Promise:**

A Promise can exist in exactly **one of three states** at any given time:

| State | Description | Transition |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **`pending`** | Initial state — operation is still in progress, neither resolved nor rejected | → fulfilled or rejected |
| **`fulfilled`** | Operation completed successfully — Promise has a resolved `value` | Terminal (immutable) |
| **`rejected`** | Operation failed — Promise has a `reason` (error) | Terminal (immutable) |

**Key Property:** Once a Promise is **settled** (fulfilled or rejected), its state **CANNOT change** — this is called **immutability**.

**Example:**
```javascript
function fetchMarks(rollNo) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      if (rollNo > 0 && rollNo <= 100) {
        resolve({ rollNo, marks: 85 });
      } else {
        reject(new Error("Invalid roll number"));
      }
    }, 500);
  });
}

fetchMarks(42)
  .then(result => console.log("Success:", result))
  .catch(err => console.error("Failed:", err.message));
```

**Output (if rollNo=42):** `Success: {rollNo: 42, marks: 85}`

**Promise Chaining:** `.then()` returns a new Promise, enabling sequential async operations:
```javascript
fetchMarks(42)
  .then(result => fetchSubjects(result.rollNo))
  .then(subjects => console.log(subjects))
  .catch(err => console.error(err));
```

