#### (b) — 7 Marks

**Compare JSON and XML as data interchange formats. Write a JavaScript program to fetch data from a JSON file and display it on a webpage using the Fetch API.**

**Model Answer:**

**JSON vs XML — Detailed Comparison:**

| Parameter | JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) | XML (Extensible Markup Language) |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **Origin** | Derived from JavaScript object syntax | W3C standard, SGML descendant |
| **Syntax** | Key-value pairs with `{}` and `[]` | Custom tags with `<>` |
| **Data Types** | String, number, boolean, null, array, object | All values are **strings** |
| **Parsing** | Native `JSON.parse()` in JavaScript | Requires XML parser (DOMParser, SAX) |
| **Size** | **~30-40% smaller** payload | Verbose, larger payload |
| **Comments** | ❌ Not allowed | ✅ Allowed `<!-- comment -->` |
| **Arrays** | Native support `[]` | No native array support |
| **Schema** | JSON Schema (optional) | XSD, DTD |
| **Readability** | Highly readable for data | Highly readable for documents |
| **Speed** | **Faster** parsing | Slower parsing |
| **Use Cases** | REST APIs, mobile apps, config | SOAP, document storage, RSS |
| **Encoding** | UTF-8 (default), UTF-16, UTF-32 | UTF-8, UTF-16 |

**JSON Example:**
```json
{ "name": "Anu", "cgpa": 9.2, "skills": ["JS", "React"] }
```

**XML Equivalent:**
```xml
<student>
  <name>Anu</name>
  <cgpa>9.2</cgpa>
  <skills>
    <skill>JS</skill>
    <skill>React</skill>
  </skills>
</student>
```

**Program — Fetch and Display JSON Data (Fetch API):**

**Step 1:** `data.json`
```json
{
  "title": "KTU Toppers 2024",
  "students": [
    { "id": 1, "name": "Anu",   "cgpa": 9.5 },
    { "id": 2, "name": "Rahul", "cgpa": 9.3 },
    { "id": 3, "name": "Meera", "cgpa": 9.4 }
  ]
}
```

**Step 2:** `index.html`
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head><title>JSON Fetch Demo</title></head>
<body>
  <h1 id="title"></h1>
  <ul id="list"></ul>
  <script src="app.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Step 3:** `app.js`
```javascript
async function loadData() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch("data.json");

    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP Error: ${response.status}`);
    }

    const data = await response.json();

    document.getElementById("title").textContent = data.title;

    const list = document.getElementById("list");
    data.students.forEach(student => {
      const li = document.createElement("li");
      li.textContent = `${student.name} - CGPA: ${student.cgpa}`;
      list.appendChild(li);
    });
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Failed to load data:", error.message);
  }
}

loadData();
```

**Output on Webpage:**
```
KTU Toppers 2024
• Anu - CGPA: 9.5
• Rahul - CGPA: 9.3
• Meera - CGPA: 9.4
```

**Explanation of Key Methods:**
- `fetch(url)` → Returns a `Promise<Response>`. Default method is **GET**.
- `response.ok` → Boolean, `true` if HTTP status is 200–299.
- `response.json()` → Parses the body as JSON, returns a `Promise<Object>`.
- `try/catch` → Handles both network failures and JSON parse errors.

