#### (b) — 7 Marks

**Explain the working of `XMLHttpRequest` (XHR) object in AJAX. Write a program to fetch data from a server using XHR and display it.**

**Model Answer:**

**The `XMLHttpRequest` (XHR) Object:**

> [!NOTE]
> The `XMLHttpRequest` object is a **browser-provided API** that enables JavaScript to make **HTTP requests** to a server **without reloading the page**. It is the **classical implementation of AJAX**, introduced by Microsoft in **1999** (IE5) and standardized by the **W3C**.

**XHR Properties and Methods:**

| Property/Method | Description |
|:---|:---|
| `new XMLHttpRequest()` | Creates a new XHR object |
| `open(method, url, async)` | Configures the request; `async=true` for AJAX |
| `send(body)` | Sends the request to the server |
| `onreadystatechange` | Event handler fired on every state change |
| `readyState` | Current state: 0=UNSENT, 1=OPENED, 2=HEADERS_RECEIVED, 3=LOADING, 4=DONE |
| `status` | HTTP status code (200, 404, 500, etc.) |
| `statusText` | Status text ("OK", "Not Found") |
| `responseText` | Response body as a string |
| `responseXML` | Response body as an XML document |
| `onload` | Event fired when request completes successfully (state 4) |
| `onerror` | Event fired on network failure |
| `setRequestHeader(name, value)` | Sets a custom HTTP header |

**The 5-State Lifecycle of XHR:**

$$ \text{State } 0 \rightarrow 1 \rightarrow 2 \rightarrow 3 \rightarrow 4 $$

- **State 0 — UNSENT:** Object created, `open()` not called.
- **State 1 — OPENED:** `open()` called, request configured.
- **State 2 — HEADERS_RECEIVED:** `send()` called, HTTP headers received.
- **State 3 — LOADING:** Response body is being downloaded.
- **State 4 — DONE:** Operation complete (success or failure).

**Program — Fetch Data Using XHR and Display:**

**Step 1: HTML File (`index.html`)**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>XHR Demo - KTU</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Student Information</h1>
  <button id="loadBtn">Load Students</button>
  <div id="output"></div>
  <script src="xhr-demo.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Step 2: JavaScript File (`xhr-demo.js`)**
```javascript
document.getElementById("loadBtn").addEventListener("click", loadStudents);

function loadStudents() {
  // Step 1: Create XHR object
  const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();

  // Step 2: Configure the request (GET, async)
  xhr.open("GET", "students.json", true);

  // Step 3: Set request header (optional, for JSON)
  xhr.setRequestHeader("Content-Type", "application/json");

  // Step 4: Define the load handler
  xhr.onload = function() {
    if (xhr.status === 200) {
      // Success
      const data = JSON.parse(xhr.responseText);
      displayStudents(data.students);
    } else {
      // HTTP error
      document.getElementById("output").innerHTML =
        `<p style="color:red;">Error: ${xhr.status} - ${xhr.statusText}</p>`;
    }
  };

  // Step 5: Define the error handler
  xhr.onerror = function() {
    document.getElementById("output").innerHTML =
      `<p style="color:red;">Network error occurred.</p>`;
  };

  // Step 6: Send the request
  xhr.send();
}

function displayStudents(students) {
  const output = document.getElementById("output");
  let html = "<ul>";
  students.forEach(s => {
    html += `<li>${s.name} - Roll: ${s.rollNo} - CGPA: ${s.cgpa}</li>`;
  });
  html += "</ul>";
  output.innerHTML = html;
}
```

**Step 3: JSON File (`students.json`)**
```json
{
  "students": [
    { "rollNo": 1, "name": "Anu",   "cgpa": 9.2 },
    { "rollNo": 2, "name": "Rahul", "cgpa": 8.8 },
    { "rollNo": 3, "name": "Meera", "cgpa": 9.5 }
  ]
}
```

**Output on Webpage (after clicking "Load Students"):**
```
Student Information
[Load Students]
• Anu - Roll: 1 - CGPA: 9.2
• Rahul - Roll: 2 - CGPA: 8.8
• Meera - Roll: 3 - CGPA: 9.5
```

**Key Points to Remember:**
- `xhr.open()` does **not** send the request — it only **configures** it.
- `xhr.send()` **actually sends** the request.
- The third parameter of `open()` is `async` — always set it to `true` for AJAX to avoid blocking the UI.
- `onload` is **preferred** over `onreadystatechange` for modern code because it fires **only when the request completes**.
- `xhr.responseText` returns a **string** — use `JSON.parse()` to convert to a JavaScript object.

