## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes that Cost Marks in KTU Exams:**
>
> 1. **Confusing `var` and `let` output in loops** — Many students predict `0,1,2` for `var` but the correct output is `3,3,3`. **Practice this example 5 times before the exam.**
>
> 2. **Forgetting to add `async` to a function that uses `await`** — This causes a `SyntaxError`. Always write `async function f() { await ... }` together.
>
> 3. **Writing `JSON.parse()` on a JavaScript object** — `parse()` takes a **JSON string**, not an object. Use `stringify()` first if you have an object. Wrong direction = **2 marks deducted**.
>
> 4. **Single quotes in JSON keys** — JSON requires **double quotes** for strings. `'name': 'Anu'` is **invalid JSON** (though valid JavaScript).
>
> 5. **Confusing XHR `readyState` numbers** — Memorize: **0=UNSENT, 1=OPENED, 2=HEADERS_RECEIVED, 3=LOADING, 4=DONE**. State 4 is when data is fully received.
>
> 6. **Forgetting `try/catch` in `async/await` code** — KTU expects proper error handling. Unhandled promise rejections = **1–2 marks lost**.
>
> 7. **Mixing up `export default` (one per file) and named `export`** — Only **one** default export per module is allowed; multiple named exports are fine.
>
> 8. **Saying "AJAX uses JSON"** — AJAX can use **JSON, XML, HTML, or plain text**. JSON is the **most common** modern format, but AJAX itself is **format-agnostic**.

