## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Anatomy of the `if` Selection Statement

The execution of an `if` statement follows a deterministic, sequential evaluation model:

1. **Evaluate** the expression within the parentheses `( )`.
2. The JavaScript engine coerces the result using the **ToBoolean** abstract operation.
3. If the coerced value is `true` → execute the **consequent block**.
4. If the coerced value is `false` → skip the consequent block; execution jumps to the statement following the `if` block.
5. Program counter resumes **sequential execution** after the construct.

### 2.2 Falsy vs. Truthy Values in JavaScript

> [!IMPORTANT]
> JavaScript has **6 falsy values**. EVERY other value is truthy. This is a **favourite KTU exam question**!

| Falsy Value | Type | Reason |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `false` | Boolean | Literal false |
| `0` | Number | Zero |
| `-0` | Number | Negative zero |
| `0n` | BigInt | BigInt zero |
| `""` | String | Empty string |
| `null` | Null | No value |
| `undefined` | Undefined | Uninitialized |
| `NaN` | Number | Not a Number |

**Truthy examples:** `"false"` (non-empty string), `[]` (empty array), `{}` (empty object), `42` (any non-zero number).

### 2.3 The `if...else if...else` Ladder

```javascript
if (condition1) {
    // Block A
} else if (condition2) {
    // Block B
} else if (condition3) {
    // Block C
} else {
    // Block D (default fallback)
}
```

- Conditions are evaluated **top-to-bottom**.
- The **first** condition to evaluate to `true` is executed; the rest are skipped.
- The `else` block is **optional** and acts as the default.

### 2.4 The `switch` Statement — Multi-Way Dispatcher

```javascript
switch (expression) {
    case value1:
        // Statements
        break;
    case value2:
        // Statements
        break;
    default:
        // Default statements
}
```

### 2.5 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Construct | Syntax | Best Used When | Strict Equality Used? | Fall-Through? |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `if` | `if (cond) { }` | Single conditional execution | Depends on operator | N/A |
| `if...else` | `if (cond) {} else {}` | Binary decisions (true/false) | Depends on operator | N/A |
| `else if` ladder | `if(c1){} else if(c2){}...` | 3+ mutually exclusive ranges | Depends on operator | N/A |
| Nested `if` | `if(c1){ if(c2){} }` | Hierarchical/complex decisions | Depends on operator | N/A |
| `switch` | `switch(expr){ case v: break; }` | One variable vs. many discrete values | **Yes (===)** | Only if `break` omitted |

### 2.6 Critical Rules for `switch`

1. **Strict Comparison (`===`)**: `case` values are compared using strict equality, so **no type coercion** occurs. `switch(1)` will **not** match `case "1"`.
2. **The `break` Statement**: Without `break`, execution **falls through** to the next `case`. This is called **switch fall-through** and is a common KTU exam pitfall.
3. **The `default` Clause**: Optional; executes when **no `case` matches**. Conventionally placed last, but its position doesn't matter.
4. **Expression Type**: The `switch` expression can be of any type (number, string, boolean, even object references).

### 2.7 Real-World Engineering Utility

> [!NOTE]
> In a real-world **Single Page Application (SPA)** built with React, Angular, or Vue, the `switch` statement is often used inside **Redux reducers** to handle action types like `ADD_USER`, `DELETE_USER`, `UPDATE_USER`. The `if` statement is used in form validation middleware, route guards (`canActivate`), and conditional rendering logic. Mastering these constructs is non-negotiable for any MERN/MEAN stack developer.

