## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 📘 PART A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023, Model Paper 1]**
>
> **Q1.** Differentiate between the `if...else` statement and the `switch` statement in JavaScript. When would you prefer one over the other?

**Model Answer:**

| Aspect | `if...else` | `switch` |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Comparison | Any relational/logical operator | Strict equality (`===`) only |
| Best For | Range checks, complex conditions | Single variable vs. multiple discrete values |
| Readability | Decreases with many branches | Excellent for 5+ cases |
| Fall-through | Not applicable | Possible if `break` is omitted |

**Usage Preference:**
- Use `if...else` when conditions involve **ranges** (e.g., `marks >= 90`), **compound conditions** (e.g., `age >= 18 && hasLicense`), or **non-equality** comparisons.
- Use `switch` when a **single variable** is being compared against **multiple discrete values** (e.g., checking `day` against 0–6, or `status` against "success", "error", "pending").

> **[KTU University Exam - May 2024, Model Paper 2]**
>
> **Q2.** Explain the concept of **fall-through** in a `switch` statement with a suitable example. How can it be prevented?

**Model Answer:**

**Fall-through** is the behavior in a `switch` statement where, if a `case` matches and the `break` statement is missing, execution continues into the next `case` block, regardless of whether that case matches.

**Example:**
```javascript
let num = 1;
switch (num) {
    case 1:
        console.log("One");
        // No break here — fall-through occurs!
    case 2:
        console.log("Two");
        break;
}
// Output:
// One
// Two
```

**Prevention:** Add a `break;` statement at the end of every `case` block that should not fall through. Fall-through is intentionally used only when **multiple cases share the same code** (e.g., grouping months into seasons).

